---
// nested-read-and-cast — Chapter 038 Lesson 9 ("Reading and writing JSONB
// columns"). A 4-step AnnotatedCode walkthrough of one Drizzle query that
// reads a NESTED JSONB field (the customer's email, two levels deep) and uses
// a nested amount in the `where`. Attention lands on four different spans in
// turn: the descend operator (`->`), the land operator (`->>`), the
// bug-fixing `::numeric` cast, and the TS-side `sql<string>` type re-claim.
//
// Why this lives in an .astro component rather than inline MDX: the `code`
// prop is a string that itself contains Drizzle's `${...}` sql-fragment
// interpolation syntax plus backticks and single quotes. Authored inline in
// MDX, the `${webhookDeliveries.payload}` inside the template literal gets
// evaluated as a real JS interpolation (→ "webhookDeliveries is not defined").
// In Astro frontmatter the escaping is plain, predictable TS: `\${` is a
// literal `${` and `\`` is a literal backtick, so the code string survives
// verbatim into Expressive Code.
//
// Every step is tinted blue to match the chapter-037/038 figure family's
// anchor hue (#2563eb), per the lesson outline ("color blue on every step").

import AnnotatedCode from "../../../code/annotated-code/AnnotatedCode.astro";
import AnnotatedStep from "../../../code/annotated-code/AnnotatedStep.astro";

// The single source-of-truth code block. The `\${...}` sequences are LITERAL
// Drizzle sql-fragment interpolations in the rendered code, not JS template
// interpolations — the backslash keeps them inert here.
const code = `
const bigPaidDeliveries = await db
  .select({
    email: sql<string>\`\${webhookDeliveries.payload}->'customer'->>'email'\`,
  })
  .from(webhookDeliveries)
  .where(sql\`(\${webhookDeliveries.payload}->'data'->>'amount')::numeric > 500\`);
`;
---

<AnnotatedCode code={code} lang="ts">
  <AnnotatedStep meta={`"->'customer'" "->'data'"`} color="blue">
    <code>-&gt;</code> descends one level and keeps the result as
    <code>jsonb</code>, so you can chain another accessor onto it. Here it steps
    into the nested <code>customer</code> object, and on the filter line into
    <code>data</code>. As long as you're still descending, stay on
    <code>-&gt;</code>.
  </AnnotatedStep>

  <AnnotatedStep meta={`"->>'email'" "->>'amount'"`} color="blue">
    <code>-&gt;&gt;</code> is how you <em>land</em>. It pulls the leaf out as
    <code>text</code>. The last hop of any path you actually read is
    <code>-&gt;&gt;</code>, never <code>-&gt;</code> — <code>-&gt;</code> would
    hand you a JSON-wrapped string, quotes and all.
  </AnnotatedStep>

  <AnnotatedStep meta={`"::numeric"`} color="blue">
    The cast that makes the comparison real. Without <code>::numeric</code>,
    <code>-&gt;&gt;'amount'</code> is text and <code>&gt; 500</code> becomes a
    <em>lexical</em> string comparison where <code>'90'</code> beats
    <code>'500'</code>. This one token is the difference between a correct
    filter and a silent bug.
  </AnnotatedStep>

  <AnnotatedStep meta={`"sql<string>"`} color="blue">
    The TS-side re-claim. The builder lost the type the moment you dropped into
    a raw <code>sql</code> fragment, so <code>sql&lt;string&gt;</code> tells the
    compiler what comes back. It's a claim you're making, not something
    TypeScript verifies — Postgres guarantees the runtime type, this only
    informs the editor.
  </AnnotatedStep>
</AnnotatedCode>
